description.text:
Sometimes you have to take the case off to print something tall. NOT ANYMORE!
I found that I can print a height of 220mm (I have a E3Dv6 so I lost a tad) before the risk of the Z nuts un-thread from the Z axis threaded rods. Using these lifters, you can get that full height without pulling that case off and still having room for the wiring.

WARNING: BEFORE you print something this tall, TEST YOUR MAX height so that you know what is the maximum height you feel safe before your printer unscrews it's Z access!

If the firmware (Configuration.h):
look for _define Z_MAX_POS 201
^--This is a pound sign (but Thingiverse uses this as a formatting char)
change the 201 (or whatever number is here) to the highest Z you want to allow.

example I set mine to _define Z_MAX_POS 221
then flash your printer with the new value.

Here is a small enclosure to host a DIY version of the TL-smoothers.
This circuit is put in between the control board and a stepper. You will have to cut the cable. It's made of 8 diodes 1N5404 and is supposed to reduce vibrations when motors stop.
Work only with DRV8825. Don't know if it works with other stepper drivers.
This is a test ! If you want to do the same, do it at your own risks !
No electric nor fire security tests have been done !
The enclosure is only here to prevent shortcuts.
Original idea and conception here : http://www.engineerination.com/2015/02/drv8825-missing-steps.html
Thx to the author for his work.

WARNING : Diodes inside the case are getting hot during a long print. If you print it in PLA, cover may bend a little and fall from the case. It is recommended to print it in ABS or any matter more resistant to heat.

description.text: This model is based on Dante Station plans I found in "Modeling the ClinchField Railroad in N Scale" [Kalmbach Books, 1979, page 46]. It took some iterations to get the right level of detail for this scale model that was still printable on my MakerBot. It is scaled at 1:160 for N scale model railroads. *** Please check out a newer version of Dante Station called Dante Station - Revisited at http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:239980 It has more detail and is easier to print.

I started the design with Google Sketchup. It is a great program for architectural modeling. But it looked too perfect for an old building so I used ZBrush to age it a little. Then I exported the design and used MakerWare 2.4 to prepare the file for printing on my Replicator2 with the following settings: Infill = 10%
Layer Height = 0.200
Shells = 1
Feedrate = 40
Travel Feed = 55
Temperature = 220 I used a raft with full support. It took a less than 4 hours to print at a height of 44 mm. If you want to use these settings plus change the support angle (which I found helps with overhangs), then create a new profile using MakerBot PLA Standard and then modify the following lines: "doSupport": true,
"supportAngle": 45.0,
"layerHeight": 0.20,
"rapidMoveFeedRateXY": 55,
"extruderTemp0": 220,
"extruderTemp1": 220, [also several other places]
"numberOfShells": 1,
"feedrate": 40, [also several other places] This provides more support for overhangs than the default as well as slowing down the printer so the accuracy and quality is better.

title: HyperCube XY Joiner for Toothed Pulley - 8mm

description.text:
There are quite of few remixes of the HyperCube XY Joiner but I couldn't find one with the following features:

  • Dual LM8UU Bearings (also IGUS RJUM-01-08 Bearings 2-3-2018)
  • 8 mm X axis, 8 mm bearing Y axis
  • Toothed Pulley mounts
  • Integrated nut pockets
  • 2-6-2018 - I added a design for IGUS RJUM-01-08 Bearings & 10 mm X axis bearing rods

I decided to try toothed pulleys because I noticed some faint lines at 2 mm spacing on the flat sides of my prints. I suspected that these lines are artifacts of the belt riding across the unsupported ridges as it turns on the smooth pulleys. The toothed pulleys do eliminate the faint lines. You may also twist the belts and use the stock back to back bearings to avoid the lines.

This is a remix of the original HyperCube XY Joiner and another XY Joiner with the dual bearing mounts for the Y axis. Both original designs are credited The bearing pockets will take 2 LM8UU bearings exactly or one LM8LUU bearing with 4 mm to spare.

This XY Joiner works well with this toothed idler:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2186358

BOM:
4pcs. LM8UU Bearings or 2pcs LM8LUU Bearings
8pcs. M3 x 18mm Socket Cap Bolts
8pcs. M3 x 16mm Socket Cap Bolts
16pcs. M3 Hex Nuts regular or Nyloc
2pcs. 16T Aluminum Timing Drive Pulley
2pcs. 16T GT2 Aluminum Timing Drive Pulley

Be sure to print with supports.

One source for the pulleys:
https://www.amazon.com and then search for "B01BTTEQU0"
https://www.amazon.com and then search for "B01BTTERC2"
Quality may vary so check reviews from wherever you order the pulleys.

Here's my HyperCube:
https://www.thingiverse.com/make:272257

UPDATE 2-6-2018: I have added two versions of the XY joiner and bearing cap for the IGUS RJUM-01-08 which is a 16 mm in diameter and 25 mm long bearing (8 mm bearing shaft). One version is for 8 mm X axis and the other is for 10 mm X axis. The bearing pockets for the Y axis fit the 16 mm diameter 25 mm long IGUS bearings. These designs have not been printed or tested so let me know if they work.
UPDATE 3-11-2018: There was a problem with the IGUS version where the bottom 2 layers did not touch the build surface Version 2 of each solves this problem.

A Nautilus submarine from 20,000 Leagues Under the Sea has been captured and sealed in a bottle!
This is the same model from the "Fleet of Nautilus" thing that I created earlier with an accompanying bottle.
The bottle is printed in natural transparent PLA (standard resolution, 1 shell and 0% infill).

The models were printed on a MakerBot Replicator 2 in PLA.
Don't use supports.
A raft is recommended for the bottle to make sure that it doesn't come loose during the build.
I scaled the models by %1000 to get the objects you see in the pictures (If you print smaller, you may have trouble because some of the Nautilus features are quite thin).
Here is the recipe:
1) Print the Nautilus halves, flat side on the build platform
2) Glue them together and decorate (paint it, glue wiggly eyes for the window(s) etc)
3) Print the bottle upside down (with the top on the build platform).
4) Use standard resolution, 1 shell, and 0% infill (standard resolution seems to give the best "transparent" result).
5) IMPORTANT: At about 95% through the build pause the build in sleep mode (on a Replicator 2 this will move the print head out of the way)
6) Carefully insert the Nautilus nose down.
7) Resume the build At the end you should have a nicely sealed and trapped Nautilus!

description.text:
This rocket fits on the launch tube of the air-powered system made by AirRocketWorks.com. The fin collar is separate so that you can launch with and without fins to see the difference in flight. You can then fashion your own fins out of cardboard and fit them into the collar to see how shape and size impact flight. The collar has a groove to fit onto a ridge on the rocket that keeps the collar from spinning. Also, I found that the collars break every 10-15 launches, so I print extras.

The Air Rocket Works system is quite powerful, so careful adult supervision and protective eyewear are required.
